[src:selenium/headless-browser] A **headless browser** is a web browser without a graphical user interface.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] Headless browsers provide automated control of a web page in an environment similar to popular web browsers, but they are executed via a command-line interface or using network communication.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] They are particularly useful for testing web pages as they are able to render and understand HTML the same way a browser would, including styling elements such as page layout, color, font selection and execution of JavaScript and Ajax which are usually not available when using other testing methods.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] Since version 59 of Google Chrome and version 56 of Firefox, there is native support for remote control of the browser.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] This made earlier efforts obsolete, notably PhantomJS.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] Headless browsers are also useful for web scraping.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] Google stated in 2009 that using a headless browser could help their search engine index content from websites that use Ajax.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] However, a study of browser traffic in 2018 found no preference by malicious actors for headless browsers.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] There is no indication that headless browsers are used more frequently than non-headless browsers for malicious purposes, like DDoS attacks, SQL injections or cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] As several major browsers natively support headless mode through APIs, some software exists to perform browser automation through a unified interface.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] Some test automation software and frameworks include headless browsers as part of their testing apparati.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] Another approach is to use software that provides browser APIs.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] For example, Deno provides browser APIs as part of its design.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] For Node.js, jsdom is the most complete provider.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] While most are able to support common browser features (HTML parsing, cookies, XHR, some JavaScript, etc.), they do not render the DOM and have limited support for DOM events.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] They usually perform faster than full browsers, but are unable to correctly interpret many popular websites.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] Another is HtmlUnit, a headless browser written in Java.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] HtmlUnit uses the Rhino engine to provide JavaScript and Ajax support as well as partial rendering capability.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] These are various software that provide headless browser APIs.
[src:selenium/headless-browser] An earlier effort (2008) was envjs from John Resig, which was a simulated browser environment written in JavaScript for the Rhino engine.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium was originally developed by Jason Huggins in 2004 as an internal tool at ThoughtWorks.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Huggins was later joined by other programmers and testers at ThoughtWorks, before Paul Hammant joined the team and steered the development of the second mode of operation that would later become "Selenium Remote Control" (RC).
[src:selenium/selenium-software] In 2005 Dan Fabulich and Nelson Sproul (with help from Pat Lightbody) made an offer to accept a series of patches that would transform Selenium-RC into what it became best known for.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] In the same meeting, the steering of Selenium as a project would continue as a committee, with Huggins and Hammant being the ThoughtWorks representatives.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Together with others like Jennifer Bevan, he continued with the development and stabilization of Selenium RC.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] At the same time, Simon Stewart at ThoughtWorks developed a superior browser automation tool called WebDriver.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] In 2009, after a meeting between the developers at the Google Test Automation Conference, it was decided to merge the two projects, and call the new project Selenium WebDriver, or Selenium 2.0.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] In 2008, Philippe Hanrigou (then at ThoughtWorks) made "Selenium Grid", which provides a hub allowing the running of multiple Selenium tests concurrently on any number of local or remote systems, thus minimizing test execution time.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Grid offered, as open source, a similar capability to the internal/private Google cloud for Selenium RC.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Pat Lightbody had already made a private cloud for "HostedQA" which he went on to sell to Gomez, Inc.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] The name Selenium comes from a joke made by Huggins in an email, mocking a competitor named Mercury, saying that mercury poisoning can be cured by taking supplements of the element selenium.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] The others that received the email took the name and ran with it.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium is composed of several components with each taking on a specific role in aiding the development of web application test automation.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium IDE is a complete integrated development environment (IDE) for Selenium tests.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] It is implemented as a Firefox Add-On and as a Chrome Extension.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] It allows for recording, editing and debugging of functional tests.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] It was previously known as Selenium Recorder.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium-IDE was originally created by Shinya Kasatani and donated to the Selenium project in 2006.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium IDE began being actively maintained in 2018.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Scripts may be automatically recorded and edited manually providing autocompletion support and the ability to move commands around quickly.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Scripts are recorded in *Selenese*, a special test scripting language for Selenium.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenese provides commands for performing actions in a browser (click a link, select an option) and for retrieving data from the resulting pages.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenese serves as the language for composing Selenium Commands, which are utilized in the testing of web applications.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] These commands, tailored to the HTML tags of UI elements, facilitate the verification of their existence.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] They guide Selenium in comprehending the specific actions or operations to execute.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] As an alternative to writing tests in Selenese, tests can also be written in various programming languages.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] These tests then communicate with Selenium by calling methods in the Selenium Client API.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium currently provides client APIs for Java, C#, Ruby, JavaScript, R and Python.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium Remote Control (RC) is a server, written in Java, that accepts commands for the browser via HTTP.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] RC makes it possible to write automated tests for a web application in any programming language, which allows for better integration of Selenium in existing unit test frameworks.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] To make writing tests easier, Selenium project currently provides client drivers for PHP, Python, Ruby, .NET, Perl and Java.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] The Java driver can also be used with JavaScript (via the Rhino engine).
[src:selenium/selenium-software] An instance of selenium RC server is needed to launch html test case - which means that the port should be different for each parallel run.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] However, for Java/PHP test case only one Selenium RC instance needs to be running continuously.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium Remote Control was a refactoring of Driven Selenium or Selenium B designed by Paul Hammant, credited with Jason as co-creator of Selenium.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] The original version directly launched a process for the browser in question, from the test language of Java, .NET, Python or Ruby.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] The wire protocol (called 'Selenese' in its day) was reimplemented in each language port.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] After the refactor by Dan Fabulich and Nelson Sproul (with help from Pat Lightbody) there was an intermediate daemon process between the driving test script and the browser.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] The benefits included the ability to drive remote browsers and the reduced need to port every line of code to an increasingly growing set of languages.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] *Selenium Remote Control* completely took over from the Driven Selenium code-line in 2006.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] The browser pattern for 'Driven'/'B' and 'RC' was response/request, which subsequently became known as Comet.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium RC served as the flagship testing framework of the entire project of selenium for a long-standing time.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium RC is the first and foremost automated web testing tool that enabled users to adopt their preferred programming language.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] With the release of Selenium 2, Selenium RC has been officially deprecated in favor of Selenium WebDriver.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] At the core of Selenium is Selenium WebDriver, an interface to write instructions that work interchangeably across browsers.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium WebDriver accepts commands (sent in Selenese, or via a Client API) and sends them to a browser.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] This is implemented through a browser-specific browser driver, which sends commands to a browser and retrieves results.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Most browser drivers actually launch and access a browser application (such as Firefox, Google Chrome, Internet Explorer, Safari, or Microsoft Edge); there is also an HtmlUnit browser driver, which simulates a browser using the headless browser HtmlUnit.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Since Selenium 4 and Google Chrome version 109, headless mode has been supported through a native implementation of the browser, in which Chrome operates without a graphical user interface but with rendering and execution behavior identical to the regular mode.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Unlike in Selenium 1, where the Selenium server was necessary to run tests, Selenium WebDriver does not need a special server to execute tests.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Instead, the WebDriver directly starts a browser instance and controls it.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] However, Selenium Grid can be used with WebDriver to execute tests on remote systems (see below).
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Where possible, WebDriver uses native operating system level functionality rather than browser-based JavaScript commands to drive the browser.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] This bypasses problems with subtle differences between native and JavaScript commands, including security restrictions.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] As of early 2012, Simon Stewart (inventor of WebDriver), who was then with Google, and David Burns of Mozilla were negotiating with the W3C to make WebDriver an Internet standard.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] In July 2012, the working draft was released and the recommendation followed in June 2018.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium WebDriver (Selenium 2.0) is fully implemented and supported in JavaScript (Node.js), Python, Ruby, Java, Kotlin, and C#.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] As of 2021, Selenium 4 is a release candidate.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium Grid is a server that allows tests to use web browser instances running on remote machines.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] With Selenium Grid, one server acts as the central hub.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Tests contact the hub to obtain access to browser instances.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] The hub has a list of servers that provide access to browser instances (WebDriver nodes), and lets tests use these instances.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] Selenium Grid allows running tests in parallel on multiple machines and to manage different browser versions and browser configurations centrally (instead of in each individual test).
[src:selenium/selenium-software] The ability to run tests on remote browser instances is useful to spread the load of testing across several machines and to run tests in browsers running on different platforms or operating systems.
[src:selenium/selenium-software] The latter is particularly useful in cases where not all browsers to be used for testing can run on the same platform.
[src:selenium/web-testing] A web application performance tool (WAPT) is used to test web applications and web related interfaces.
[src:selenium/web-testing] These tools are used for performance, load and stress testing of web applications, web sites, web API, web servers and other web interfaces.
[src:selenium/web-testing] WAPT tends to simulate virtual users which will repeat either recorded URLs or specified URL and allows the users to specify number of times or iterations that the virtual users will have to repeat the recorded URLs.
[src:selenium/web-testing] By doing so, the tool is useful to check for bottleneck and performance leakage in the website or web application being tested.
[src:selenium/web-testing] WAPT allows a user to specify how virtual users are involved in the testing environment.ie either increasing users or constant users or periodic users load.
[src:selenium/web-testing] Increasing user load, step by step is called RAMP where virtual users are increased from 0 to hundreds.
[src:selenium/web-testing] Constant user load maintains specified user load at all time.
[src:selenium/web-testing] Periodic user load tends to increase and decrease the user load from time to time.
[src:selenium/web-testing] Web security testing tells us whether Web-based applications requirements are met when they are subjected to malicious input data.
[src:selenium/web-testing] An application programming interface API exposes services to other software components, which can query the API.
[src:selenium/web-testing] The API implementation is in charge of computing the service and returning the result to the component that send the query.
[src:selenium/web-testing] A part of web testing focuses on testing these web API implementations.
[src:selenium/web-testing] GraphQL is a specific query and API language.
[src:selenium/web-testing] It is the focus of tailored testing techniques.
[src:selenium/web-testing] Search-based test generation yields good results to generate test cases for GraphQL APIs.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] Perhaps the most common challenge for browser automation is ensuring that the web application is in a state to execute a particular Selenium command as desired.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] The processes often end up in a *race condition* where sometimes the browser gets into the right state first (things work as intended) and sometimes the Selenium code executes first (things do not work as intended).
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] This is one of the primary causes of *flaky tests*.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] All navigation commands wait for a specific `readyState` value based on the page load strategy (the default value to wait for is `"complete"`) before the driver returns control to the code.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] The `readyState` only concerns itself with loading assets defined in the HTML, but loaded JavaScript assets often result in changes to the site, and elements that need to be interacted with may not yet be on the page when the code is ready to execute the next Selenium command.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] Similarly, in a lot of single page applications, elements get dynamically added to a page or change visibility based on a click.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] An element must be both present and displayed on the page in order for Selenium to interact with it.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] Take this page for example: https://www.selenium.dev/selenium/web/dynamic.html When the “Add a box!” button is clicked, a “div” element that does not exist is created.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] When the “Reveal a new input” button is clicked, a hidden text field element is displayed.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] In both cases the transition takes a couple seconds.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] If the Selenium code is to click one of these buttons and interact with the resulting element, it will do so before that element is ready and fail.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] The first solution many people turn to is adding a sleep statement to pause the code execution for a set period of time.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] Because the code can’t know exactly how long it needs to wait, this can fail when it doesn’t sleep long enough.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] Alternately, if the value is set too high and a sleep statement is added in every place it is needed, the duration of the session can become prohibitive.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] Selenium provides two different mechanisms for synchronization that are better.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] Selenium has a built-in way to automatically wait for elements called an *implicit wait*.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] An implicit wait value can be set either with the timeouts capability in the browser options, or with a driver method (as shown below).
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] This is a global setting that applies to every element location call for the entire session.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] The default value is `0`, which means that if the element is not found, it will immediately return an error.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] If an implicit wait is set, the driver will wait for the duration of the provided value before returning the error.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] Note that as soon as the element is located, the driver will return the element reference and the code will continue executing, so a larger implicit wait value won’t necessarily increase the duration of the session.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] This example shows the condition being waited for as a *lambda*.
[src:selenium/webdriver-waits] The Wait class can be instantiated with various parameters that will change how the conditions are evaluated.
